-- 
South Africa Stocks: Anglo, ArcelorMittal, Curro, Kumba, SAB

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-15T15:44:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-15/stocks-in-south-africa-rally-for-fourth-day-bhp-billiton-anglogold-move.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rose for a fourth day, gaining 333.02, or 1.1 percent, to
30,159.42 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg. The index rose 2
percent last week.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the mining company that makes
up about 9 percent of the benchmark  stock index , rose for a
third day, adding 3.55 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 286.65 rand.
Copper gained as much as 1.3 percent as better-than-expected
gross domestic product data from  Japan  and U.S. retail sales
improved  market sentiment  over the global economic outlook.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s biggest mining
group, closed at its highest since Aug. 2, rising 2.85 rand, or
1.2 percent, to 238.49 rand.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd. (ACL)  , Africa’s largest
Steelmaker, fell 31 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 61.99 rand,
snapping two days of gains. The company said it could lose about
400,000 metric tons of steel after a structural failure at its
Newcastle gas cleaning plant.  Curro Holdings Ltd. (COH SJ), an operator of private
schools, fell to the lowest since its started trading in
Johannesburg on June 3, dropping 40 cents, or 7 percent, to 5.30
rand. The company reported a loss of 9.6 cents per share for the
six months to June, compared with earnings of 2.9 cents a year
earlier.  Group Five Ltd. (GRF SJ), a South African construction
company, fell for the first day in four, dropping 19 cents, or
0.7 percent, to 28.32 rand. The company reported a fiscal full-
year loss and said that “short-term earnings” are likely to
remain under pressure.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-largest
gold producer, declined for a second day, dropping 4.61 rand, or
4.7 percent, to 94.39 rand. The miner posted a fiscal fourth-
quarter loss after writing down the value of mining assets.  Kumba Iron Ore Ltd. (KIO)  , an iron ore-producing unit of
 Anglo American Plc (AAL) , fell for a second day, easing 4.10 rand, or
0.9 percent, to 464 rand. The company was downgraded to
“neutral” from “outperform” at Credit Suisse Group AG by
equity analyst Semyon Mironov, with a price estimate of 500 rand
per share.  Optimum Coal Holdings (OPT)  Ltd, a coal producer,
climbed the most since it started trading in March 2010, rising
2.10 rand, or 8.8 percent, to 26 rand. The group said full-year
profit through June probably climbed more than 20 percent.  SABMiller Plc (SAB)  , the world’s second-largest brewer
by volume, advanced for a fourth day, gaining 2.87 rand, or 1.2
percent, to 245.74 rand. The brewer was raised to “overweight”
from “equal weight” at  Barclays Capital  by equity analyst
Simon Hales, with a price estimate of 23.50 pounds per share.  SacOil Holding Ltd. (SCL)  , an African oil and natural-
gas explorer, rose the most in 13 months, advancing 11 cents, or
20 percent, to 65 cents. The group said it was making progress
on its oil concession in the Democratic Republic of Congo.  To contact the reporter on this story:
